Introduction and project goal

In this project, the goal is to develop a parsimonious linear predictive model for house prices in Ames, Iowa, using a dataset split into training and test sets (with 1,460 and 1,459 observations, respectively). Model performance benchmark for minimum estimated out-of-sample R^2 is .75.

The target variable, SalePrice, is provided in the training set but omitted from the test set, challenging us to build a model that generalizes well to unseen data.

In this notebook, I will choose 5 predictors representing different aspects of a property namely MSSubClass, HouseStyle, Neighborhood, OverallQual and SaleType. Below is data description:

  • SalePrice (target variable) - the propertys sale price in dollars.

  • MSSubClass: The building class

  • Utilities: Type of utilities available

  • Neighborhood: Physical locations within Ames city limits

  • OverallQual: Overall material and finish quality

  • SaleType: Type of sale

More details of the data can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/data

It seems like the datatype is correct and there is no anomaly in our data. However, in the test set, there is one NA value in MSSubClass and SaleType.

According to data dictionary, NA values in these columns do not have any special meaning and indicate missing value. We will replace these missing values with the most frequently occuring value of its field.

# Define mode function 
get_mode <- function(x) {
  unique_x <- unique(x)
  unique_x[which.max(tabulate(match(x, unique_x)))]
}

# Replace NA values in MSSubClass with its mode 
test$MSSubClass[is.na(test$MSSubClass)] <- get_mode(test$MSSubClass)

# Replace NA values in SaleType with its mode 
test$SaleType[is.na(test$SaleType)] <- get_mode(test$SaleType)

# Verify there are no NA values left in these columns
sum(is.na(test$MSSubClass))  
## [1] 0
sum(is.na(test$SaleType))     
## [1] 0

We finished handling missing values. Now, we will develop parsimonious linear model using 5 predictors additively.

3. Data modelling

We will take a look at 2 categorical features: OverallQual and MSSubClass.

OverallQual and MSSubClass are categorical features but encoded as numeric. If they are non-linearly related to the target then they should be encoded as factor. If the relationship is linear we will keep them numeric.

# Check the relationship between SalePrice and OverallQual
train |> 
  ggplot(aes(factor(OverallQual), SalePrice)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "SalePrice ~ OverallQual")

This is more of an exponential increase, which is not well described by a line.

# Plot a regression line vs. a non-linear fit (LOESS)
ggplot(train, aes(as.numeric(OverallQual), SalePrice)) +

  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +

  labs(title = "SalePrice ~ OverallQual, with linear and local regression") +

4. Cross-validation

First, we will divide the training set into two folds (train fold and validation fold), with a split ratio of 70/30.

Create an index of random 70% of rows:

# Randomly sample 70% of the rows in an object called index
set.seed(124)
index <- sample(x = 1:nrow(train), size = nrow(train)*.7, replace = F)

# Check
head(index) 
## [1] 1345  167 1002 1435  261  728

Use the index to create a random 70/30 split of the data:

# Subset train using index to create a 70% train_fold
train_fold <- train[index, ]

# Subset the remaining rows not included in index to create a 30% validation fold
validation_fold <- train[-index, ]

Second, we will fit the model to the train fold and evaluate it on the validation fold. The RMSE and R-squared values on the validation fold will serve as estimates of the models performance on unseen data.

# Fit example model
model <- lm(SalePrice ~ MSSubClass + HouseStyle + Neighborhood + OverallQual + SaleType, data = train_fold)

# Get predictions for the validation fold
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = validation_fold)

# Create functions for calculating RMSE and R-squared (necessary for estimating 
# out of sample performance)

rmse <- function(observed, predicted) sqrt(mean((observed - predicted)^2))

R2 <- function(observed, predicted){
  TSS <- sum((observed - mean(observed))^2)
  RSS <- sum((observed - predicted)^2)
  1- RSS/TSS
}

# Estimated out of sample RMSE
rmse(validation_fold$SalePrice, predictions)
## [1] 41372.49
# Estimated out of sample R-squared
R2(validation_fold$SalePrice, predictions)
## [1] 0.7510237

This model meets the minimum required benchmark of .75 estimated out of sample R-squared.

Therefore, we wil fit the model using the entire train set and calculate in sample performance

# Fit the model to the entire train set.
submission_model <- lm(SalePrice ~ MSSubClass + HouseStyle + Neighborhood + OverallQual + SaleType, data = train)

# R-squared and RMSE for this model will be the estimated in-sample model performance

5. Model fitting

Now, we will factor MSSubClass and OverallQual in test set as we did in train set.

# Copy changes made to train in Test
test <- test |> 
  mutate(
    MSSubClass = factor(MSSubClass),
    OverallQual = factor(OverallQual)
  )

Now we will use the model to predict the missing SalePrice in the test set. There is a new level 150 for MSSubClass. Therefore, we will align factor levels between train and test data.

# Ensure both training and test sets have the same factor levels
train$MSSubClass <- factor(train$MSSubClass)
test$MSSubClass <- factor(test$MSSubClass, levels = levels(train$MSSubClass))

# Make predictions
submission_predictions <- predict(submission_model, newdata = test)
